related_questions.question: What is FY24?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: Fiscal Year vs. Calendar Year: While the calendar year runs from January 1 to December 31, a fiscal year can start and end on different dates.

US Federal Government: The US federal government's fiscal year runs from October 1 to September 30. Therefore, FY24 for the federal government means the period from October 1, 2023, to September 30, 2024.
Other Entities: Businesses and other organizations can also have their own fiscal years, which may differ from the calendar year and the US federal government's fiscal year.
Importance: The fiscal year is crucial for financial reporting, budgeting, and tax purposes.
Naming Convention: Fiscal years are typically named after the year in which they end. For example, a fiscal year ending in 2024 is called FY24.

related_questions.question: What is FY25?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: Fiscal Year (FY): A fiscal year is a 12-month period that a company, organization, or government uses for financial reporting and budgeting. It doesn't always align with the calendar year (January 1 to December 31).
US Federal Government FY25: For the US federal government, the fiscal year begins on October 1st and ends on September 30th of the following year.
Why the Name? Fiscal years are typically named after the calendar year in which they end. So, FY25 refers to the year ending in 2025.

Continuing Resolution: In the case of the US federal government in FY25, they are operating under a full-year continuing resolution, which essentially extends the 2024 budget with limited changes, according to Wikipedia.
